<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ssh-hardening">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>server-craft</domain>
    <summary>OpenSSH hardening for Ubuntu/Debian VPS: key-only auth (ed25519), drop-in sshd_config.d/, modern crypto, port change via systemd socket override, client config with multiplexing.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>ssh</tag>
      <tag>security</tag>
      <tag>ubuntu</tag>
      <tag>hardening</tag>
      <tag>systemd</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>SSH Hardening</title>
    <summary>OpenSSH server hardening for Ubuntu/Debian VPS: key-only authentication (ed25519), drop-in config via `sshd_config.d/`, modern crypto (curve25519 KEX + AEAD ciphers), port change via systemd socket override, and client `~/.ssh/config` with connection multiplexing. The critical safety rule is: always keep a second terminal session open and test the new connection BEFORE closing the original session.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Default OpenSSH configs are permissive for compatibility. SSH is the primary public attack surface on any VPS. Key-only auth eliminates brute-force password attacks entirely. ed25519 is faster and more secure than RSA. Drop-in `sshd_config.d/` files survive package upgrades. Ubuntu 24.04 uses systemd socket activation — changing `Port` in `sshd_config` alone does not work; the socket override is required.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Bootstrapping a new VPS — SSH hardening is required before any other service is exposed</item>
        <item>After adding a new user who needs SSH access — `AllowUsers` must be updated</item>
        <item>Auditing an existing server's SSH config against Mozilla SSH guidelines</item>
        <item>Rotating SSH keys (compromised key, new machine)</item>
        <item>Configuring SSH client for multi-server workflows with ProxyJump</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Servers already behind Tailscale/WireGuard where SSH is not reachable from the public internet (still good practice, but urgency is lower)</item>
        <item>Ephemeral containers or CI runners — hardening overhead not worth it for short-lived instances</item>
        <item>Servers with a vetted existing config — re-running risks lockout if the second-terminal test sequence is skipped</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="server-hardening">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always write custom SSH settings to /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-hardening.conf rather than editing /etc/ssh/sshd_config directly. Drop-in files survive OpenSSH package upgrades.</statement>
        <rationale>Editing sshd_config directly risks losing changes on package upgrade. Drop-in files in sshd_config.d/ are merged alphabetically (later files win) and survive upgrades cleanly.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/99-hardening.conf">Complete drop-in sshd config file</reference>

      <rule>
        <statement>Set PasswordAuthentication no, ChallengeResponseAuthentication no, KbdInteractiveAuthentication no, and PubkeyAuthentication yes. Keep UsePAM yes for session management.</statement>
        <rationale>Key-only auth eliminates brute-force password attacks entirely. ChallengeResponseAuthentication and KbdInteractiveAuthentication are alternative names for the same mechanism — both must be disabled to fully block keyboard-interactive login.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <section name="access-control">
        <list>
          <item>PermitRootLogin no — never allow direct root SSH</item>
          <item>AllowUsers nero — whitelist specific users (space-separated for multiple)</item>
          <item>MaxAuthTries 3 — lock out after 3 failed attempts</item>
          <item>LoginGraceTime 30 — 30 seconds to authenticate</item>
          <item>MaxSessions 10 — enough for AI agent parallel SSH (increase to 20 for heavy agent use)</item>
        </list>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Setting AllowUsers in multiple drop-in files. The last file alphabetically wins, silently excluding users set in earlier files.</description>
          <reason>Consolidate AllowUsers into a single drop-in file to avoid invisible user lockout.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>

      <section name="crypto-hardening">
        <rule>
          <statement>Restrict KexAlgorithms to curve25519 and sntrup761 hybrid. Restrict Ciphers to AEAD-only (chacha20-poly1305, aes256-gcm, aes128-gcm). Remove weak host keys (RSA, ECDSA) and keep only ssh_host_ed25519_key.</statement>
          <rationale>Default OpenSSH includes legacy algorithms for compatibility. Restricting to modern algorithms prevents downgrade attacks. AEAD ciphers provide both encryption and authentication without separate MAC negotiation.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
KexAlgorithms sntrup761x25519-sha512@openssh.com,curve25519-sha256,curve25519-sha256@libssh.org
Ciphers chacha20-poly1305@openssh.com,aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-gcm@openssh.com
MACs hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com
HostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key
]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="verification">
        <rule>
          <statement>Always run sudo sshd -t to validate config syntax before restarting sshd. Follow with sudo sshd -T to show the effective merged configuration including all drop-in files.</statement>
          <rationale>sshd -t validates syntax but not runtime issues (missing host key file). Always follow with systemctl status ssh after restart to confirm the daemon is running.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="port-change">
      <rule>
        <statement>On Ubuntu 24.04, SSH uses systemd socket activation. Changing Port in sshd_config alone does NOT change the listening port. The systemd socket override file must be updated: /etc/systemd/system/ssh.socket.d/override.conf</statement>
        <rationale>The ssh.socket unit controls which port the daemon listens on via socket activation. The Port directive in sshd_config is ignored when socket activation is in use.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# /etc/systemd/system/ssh.socket.d/override.conf
[Socket]
ListenStream=
ListenStream=2222
]]></code>
        <note>ListenStream= (empty) clears the default port 22. ListenStream=2222 sets the new port.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>Execute port change in this exact order: (1) open new port in UFW, (2) create socket override, (3) reload daemon and restart socket, (4) test connection on new port in a NEW terminal, (5) only then remove old port from UFW.</statement>
        <rationale>If the new port is not opened in UFW before restarting SSH, you will be locked out. If the connection test fails and you closed the original session, you need console access to recover.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Step 1: Open new port FIRST
sudo ufw allow 2222/tcp comment "SSH"

# Step 2: Create socket override
sudo mkdir -p /etc/systemd/system/ssh.socket.d
sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/ssh.socket.d/override.conf <<'EOF'
[Socket]
ListenStream=
ListenStream=2222
EOF

# Step 3: Reload and restart
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart ssh.socket
sudo systemctl restart ssh

# Step 4: Test in a NEW terminal before closing current session
# ssh -p 2222 nero@server

# Step 5: After confirming — remove old port
sudo ufw delete allow 22/tcp
]]></code>
      </example>

      <section name="post-change-checklist">
        <list>
          <item>Update fail2ban SSH jail port to match new port</item>
          <item>Update ~/.ssh/config on all client machines</item>
          <item>Remove weak host keys: sudo rm -f /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key* /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key*</item>
          <item>Update monitoring alerts if they check SSH port availability</item>
        </list>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="client-config">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set these global defaults in ~/.ssh/config under Host *: HashKnownHosts yes, IdentitiesOnly yes, AddKeysToAgent yes, ServerAliveInterval 60, ControlMaster auto with ControlPath and ControlPersist 600.</statement>
        <rationale>IdentitiesOnly prevents SSH from trying all keys in the agent (causes "Too many authentication failures"). ControlMaster multiplexes connections, making subsequent SSH calls to the same host near-instant (important for agents that open many parallel sessions).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/ssh-client-config">Full ~/.ssh/config template with all host entries</reference>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use ProxyJump (-J or ProxyJump in config) instead of ForwardAgent for multi-hop SSH. Never enable ForwardAgent globally — only per trusted host if absolutely required.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent forwarding exposes local SSH keys on the intermediate host. If that host is compromised, all keys in the agent are accessible. ProxyJump tunnels the connection without any key material touching the intermediate host.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# ~/.ssh/config
Host prod
    HostName 10.0.1.10
    User nero
    Port 22
    ProxyJump jump.example.com
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519

# Usage: ssh prod  (automatically tunnels through jump host)
# SCP:   scp file.txt prod:/tmp/
]]></code>
      </example>

      <section name="cicd-restricted-keys">
        <rule>
          <statement>Restrict CI/CD SSH keys in authorized_keys with command= to run only the deploy script, plus no-port-forwarding, no-X11-forwarding, no-agent-forwarding, no-pty.</statement>
          <rationale>A CI/CD key with full shell access is a major security risk. The command= restriction ensures the key can only trigger the deploy script, regardless of what the CI pipeline sends as the command.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <example type="good">
          <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
command="/home/nero/workspace/deploy/deploy.sh all",no-port-forwarding,no-X11-forwarding,no-agent-forwarding,no-pty ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3... github-actions-deploy
]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="key-permissions">
        <list>
          <item>chmod 700 ~/.ssh</item>
          <item>chmod 600 ~/.ssh/config</item>
          <item>chmod 600 ~/.ssh/id_ed25519</item>
          <item>chmod 644 ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub</item>
          <item>chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Create ~/.ssh/sockets/ directory for connection multiplexing before using ControlPath. SSH will fail to create the control socket if the directory does not exist.</statement>
          <rationale>ControlPath uses a directory that must exist beforehand. mkdir -p ~/.ssh/sockets is a one-time setup step.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/99-hardening.conf" purpose="Drop-in sshd config for /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/"/>
      <template path="templates/ssh-client-config" purpose="~/.ssh/config template with global hardening and host entries"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
